  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The individual contribution of the specific injuring mechanisms surgical trauma,
      extracorporeal circulation, and ischemia/reperfusion to clinical outcome in coronary
      revascularisation remains to be elucidated. The effect of these factors is analyzed in this
      randomized clinical trial by comparing the 3 surgical approaches: Conventional Coronary
      Artery Bypass Grafting (CCAB), with extracorporeal circulation and cardioplegic arrest;
      Off-Pump Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (OPCAB), avoids extracorporeal circulation and
      global myocardial ischemia; and Pump-Assisted Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (PACAB), with
      an unloaded and beating heart. The hypothesis addressed by the study is that the surgical
      invasiveness increases in the order: OPCAB, PACAB, CCAB.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
